    <statement><p>Add or subtract the rational expressions to a single rational expression and then simplify. If applicable, state the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{6y}{y+4}+\frac{y}{y-4}-7} =}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-\frac{4\mathopen{}\left(5y-28\right)}{\left(y+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-4\right)}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{6y}{y+4}+\frac{y}{y-4}-7} 
      \amp = {\frac{6y}{y+4}} \cdot \frac{(y-4)}{(y-4)} + {\frac{y}{y-4}} \cdot \frac{(y+4)}{(y+4)} - \frac{7}{1} \cdot \frac{(y+4)(y-4)}{(y+4)(y-4)} \\
      \amp = \frac{6y(y-4)}{(y+4)(y-4)}  + \frac{y(y+4)}{(y+4)(y-4)} - \frac{7(y+4)(y-4)}{(y+4)(y-4)} \\
      \amp =  \frac{6y(y-4)+y(y+4)-7(y+4)(y-4)}{(y+4)(y-4)} \\
      \amp =  \frac{6y^{2}-24y+y^{2}+4y-7(y^{2}-16)}{(y+4)(y-4)} \\
      \amp =  \frac{6y^{2}-24y+y^{2}+4y-7y^{2}+112}{(y+4)(y-4)} \\
      \amp = {\frac{-20y+112}{\left(y+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-4\right)}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Notice that <m>{-\frac{4\mathopen{}\left(5y-28\right)}{\left(y+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-4\right)}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)}</m> is also correct. We should actually factor whenever possible, in case we can reduce the rational expression.</p>
</solution>
